<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-555-624  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 555 624.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  June 11 1990 n304 p55(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting what you deserve. (Parting Shot) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilde, Candee.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A performance-based system of salaries for communications industrymanagers and executives makes good sense on several levels.andP;  Itwould place the compensation levels of all senior management onthe same system as the Chief Executive Officer, who is rewardedcommensurate with the firm's profitability.andP;  A number of smallercompanies are beginning to adopt a compensation system offeringrelatively modest salaries along with substantial bonuses gearedto reflect profitable business operations.andP;  Long term bonussystems, however, can become a problem, as in the case of CraigMcCaw of McCaw Cellular Communications, who notched a salary of$289,000 and long term stock bonuses valued at $53 million in 1989while his company itself lost money.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SalaryExecutivePerformanceCommunications IndustryManagement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>